        &lt;figcaption&gt;Image: Universal&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="2uQfQ3"&gt;Though &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/2/11/24070183/the-new-twisters-trailer-is-a-storm-chasers-dream"&gt;Universal’s &lt;em&gt;Twisters&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;em&gt; &lt;/em&gt;is set to drop as the US deals with &lt;a href="https://www.axios.com/2024/07/15/dangerous-heat-wave-grips-east-coast"&gt;a massive heatwave&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href="https://www.npr.org/2024/07/16/nx-s1-5041344/california-wildfires-acres-calfire"&gt;wildfires&lt;/a&gt;, and &lt;a href="https://apnews.com/article/hurricane-beryl-texas-power-outages-5f4a6c563430fb49c975640c37e11872"&gt;the aftermath&lt;/a&gt; of multiple &lt;a href="https://www.hindustantimes.com/world-news/us-news/chicago-hit-by-deadly-derecho-as-storms-unleash-havoc-across-midwest-all-about-the-dangerous-weather-phenomenon-101721141691855.html"&gt;deadly storms&lt;/a&gt;, the movie goes out of its way to avoid mentioning climate change because its director didn’t want to make audiences uncomfortable.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="OVkhLt"&gt;It would have made sense if &lt;em&gt;Twisters &lt;/em&gt;— a film about storm chasers studying a spate of unusually powerful and destructive tornadoes — worked climate change into its story. But in &lt;a href="https://www.cnn.com/2024/07/16/entertainment/twisters-film-interviews-climate-change/index.html"&gt;a recent interview with CNN&lt;/a&gt;, director Lee Isaac Chung said that, even though he thinks cinema “should be a reflection of the world,” he avoided mentioning climate change in &lt;em&gt;Twisters&lt;/em&gt; because he doesn’t “feel like films are meant to be message-oriented.”&lt;/p&gt;
